<span id="freeTextContainer11981907436926165229">Although this review is placed with <u>The Skystone</u>, It&apos;s really a review of all the Camulod Chronicles books, which I&apos;ve positively devoured.<br/><br/>Whyte&apos;s portrayal of the possible history and politics of Britain after the withdrawal of the Romans is some of the best historical fiction I&apos;ve read. Whyte manages to add fantastic character and plot development to something that all the history teachers I&apos;ve ever had made boring and dry. If there were more great historical fiction writers like Whyte teachin</span>
  <span id="freeText11981907436926165229" style="display:none">Although this review is placed with <u>The Skystone</u>, It's really a review of all the Camulod Chronicles books, which I've positively devoured.<br /><br />Whyte's portrayal of the possible history and politics of Britain after the withdrawal of the Romans is some of the best historical fiction I've read. Whyte manages to add fantastic character and plot development to something that all the history teachers I've ever had made boring and dry. If there were more great historical fiction writers like Whyte teaching students a thing or two about history (both real, and possible), students would study history in much greater detail. If you're a fan of swords-and-sorcery fiction, or of historical fiction, the Camulod Chronicles should be on your must-read list.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11981907436926165229" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
